mages, exploring characters from an emotional perspective, tapping the power of color and sense memory to trigger ideas, and trying other visceral techniques. The guide also includes a troubleshooting section to help tackle problem scenes. Writers with scripts already in progress will find they can think deeper about their characters and stories. And those who are just beginning to write will find the guidance they need to discover their best starting point. The guide is filled with hundreds of examples, many of which have been developed as both plays and films. Character, Scene, and Story is fully aligned with the new edition of The Dramatic Writer’s Companion, with cross-references between related exercises so that writers have the option to explore a given topic in more depth. While both guides can stand alone, together they give writers more than one hundred tools to develop more vivid characters and craft stronger scripts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAuthorshipvHandbooks, manuals, etc. 0aAuthorshipvProblems, exercises, etc. 0aDramaxTechniquevHandbooks, manuals, etc. 0aDramaxTechniquevProblems, exercises, etc. 0aDrama--Technique--Handbooks, manuals, etc. 0aMotion picture authorshipvHandbooks, manuals, etc. 0aMotion picture authorshipvProblems, exercises, etc. 0aPlaywritingvHandbooks, manuals, etc. 0aPlaywritingvProblems, exercises, etc. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / General.2bisacsh  adrama, dramatic, playwright, plays, stage, toolbox, handbook, character, scenes, plot, story, narrative, dramatists, guide, screenwriters, film, storytelling process, scripts, writing, writers, emotions, guidance, technique, manual, author, authorship, motion picture, movie, interest, action, conflict, real world, relationship, dealing with problems, drafting.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe